VA veteran's touch
p3
sVnews
p4
VHARISH BALT.V. Sankaranarayanan's concert drew a large gathering at Bharatiya Vidya Bhavan, Kochi. He started with a sloka `Gajananam' in Natta followed by `Mahaganapathim.'Swaraprasthara, which seems to be his forte, came in mellifluous exuberance and was well received by the listeners.  A Chithranjani kriti of Tyagaraja `Nadatanumanisham Shankaram' hadswaraswitheduppuon `Sahyojathadi.'A melodiousalaapanaof Purvikalyani had briskkorvai akaras,which is characteristic of TVS' style. `Iniyakilum ninai maname,' a rarely heard kriti, appealed with its lucidity of lyrics and  expression. A kriti in Huseni raga, in misra chappu, `Gayami tava namam,' a devotional piece, was rendered with accent on thegamakason thevakrauses.MasterpieceThe vocalist's masterpiece was raga Mohanam. The kriti was Papanasam Sivan's `Kapali.' There was a vivid display of imagination and precision during the rendition. Theswara prastharawas a long exercise ofkorvaisand jarus. Violinist Nagai Sriram gave brief glimpses of his own creativity at certain points in the recital.The vocalist was accompanied by Skanda Subramaniam on the mridangam and K.V. Gopalakrishnan on the ghatom.Musical traditionKeeping aloft his musical tradition of Muthiah Bhagavathar, TVS rendered the maestro's composition `Jalandhara' in Valaji raga. Shanmukhapriya was packed with brigas and rigorous movements along the octaves.A pallavi in Triputa was followed by swaras in Behag and Brindavani. TVS is popular for his viruthams in namasankirtana, and one such followed in Yamuna Kalyani . This was followed by `Krishna nee begane baro.' TVS wound up the concert with a Sindhubhairavi piece `Ramachandraprabhu' of Swati Tirunal.The music, an ideal blend ofbhavaand richmanodharma,was matched by the rendition that was able to reach out to the audience.The concert was organised by Rasikapriya and Sree Krishna Sweet House.Bottom Template Starts
